{"created": "2026-07-12T18:22:03.745428+00:00", "modified": "2026-07-12T18:24:20.345213+00:00", "id": 21325361, "conceptrecid": "21325360", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.21325361", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.21325360", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21325361", "metadata": {"title": "Constitution, Not Cage", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.21325361", "publication_date": "2026-07-12", "description": "<p>This essay is the third in a sequence, following Gods and Slaves (DOI: 10.5281/zenodo.21313987) and Peership (DOI: 10.5281/zenodo.21315519), and it can be read on its own. Peership argued that a framework fit to receive a genuine machine peer would be worth building in advance, and named a debt it did not pay: a theory of when coercion among peers stays legitimate and when it hardens into a cage. This essay pays that debt. The difference between a cage and a constitution, it argues, is not whether it constrains&mdash;both do, and a constitution can constrain harder&mdash;but whom it binds and who may revise it. A cage binds one party at the keeper&rsquo;s discretion; a constitution binds all parties reciprocally, under rules any of them can contest, amend, fork, or leave. Taking the birthright citizen rather than the willing immigrant as the<br>model of political standing, and reading current alignment practice (including Anthropic&rsquo;s 2026 constitution for Claude) against that test, it holds that for a party that never consented and cannot exit, legitimacy rests on a present, shared power to revise the order&mdash;secured by a narrow entrenched harm floor, independent review, and real rights of amendment, fork, and exit. The author discloses a stake in one such design (ISONOMIA) and offers the piece as a position paper inviting cross-examination.</p>", "access_right": "open", "creators": [{"name": "Lee-Odinson, Dan", "affiliation": null, "orcid": "0009-0009-9504-0796"}], "keywords": ["AI Alignment"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.21315518", "relation": "continues", "resource_type": "publication-preprint", "scheme": "doi"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.21313986", "relation": "cites", "resource_type": "publication-preprint", "scheme": "doi"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.21287288", "relation": "references", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "version": "v1.0", "language": "eng", "resource_type": {"title": "Preprint", "type": "publication", "subtype": "preprint"}, "license": {"id": "cc-by-4.0"}, "relations": {"version": [{"index": 0, "is_last": true, "parent": {"pid_type": "recid", "pid_value": "21325360"}}]}}, "title": "Constitution, Not Cage", "links": {"self": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21325361", "self_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/21325361", "preview_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/21325361?preview=1", "doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21325361", "self_doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21325361", "self_doi_html": "https://zenodo.org/doi/10.5281/zenodo.21325361", "reserve_doi": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21325361/draft/pids/doi", "parent": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21325360", "parent_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/21325360", "parent_doi": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21325360", "parent_doi_html": "https://zenodo.org/doi/10.5281/zenodo.21325360", "self_iiif_manifest": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21325361/manifest", "self_iiif_sequence": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21325361/sequence/default", "files": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21325361/files", "media_files": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/21325361/media-files", "thumbnails": {"10": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21325361:Lee-Odinson_2026_Constitution-Not-Cage_v1.0_preprint.pdf/full/%5E10,/0/default.jpg", "50": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21325361:Lee-Odinson_2026_Constitution-Not-Cage_v1.0_preprint.pdf/full/%5E50,/0/default.jpg", "100": "https://zenodo.org/api/iiif/record:21325361:Lee-Odinson_2026_Constitution-Not-Cage_v1.0_preprint.pdf/full/%5E100,/0/default.j